data.content:
# .NET 8 Migration: `BackgroundProcessor`

## Critical Breaking Changes

**`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+.** `ThreadAbortException` will never be raised. Your `Stop()` method will crash and your cleanup logic in the `catch` block will never execute.

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | ❌ `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `ThreadAbortException` | ❌ Never thrown |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | ❌ `PlatformNotSupportedException` |

## Migrated Code

Use `CancellationToken` for cooperative cancellation and replace the raw `Thread` with a `Task`-based pattern:

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Task? _workerTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass the token so blocking calls can be interrupted immediately.
                // This is the key difference: GetNextItem must COOPERATE with cancellation.
                var item = GetNextItem(token);
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Replaces ThreadAbortException handling.
                // Unlike Thread.Abort(), this is cooperative — you are guaranteed
                // to be at a cancellation-safe point, not an arbitrary instruction.
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // Exit the loop cleanly (no ResetAbort needed)
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public async Task StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerTask is null)
            return;

        // Signal cancellation (replaces _running = false AND Thread.Abort)
        _cts.Cancel();

        // Wait with a timeout instead of Thread.Sleep + Abort
        var effectiveTimeout = timeout ?? TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5);
        if (await Task.WhenAny(_workerTask, Task.Delay(effectiveTimeout)) != _workerTask)
        {
            // Log warning: worker did not stop within timeout.
            // In .NET 8 there is NO way to forcibly kill it — this is by design.
            // You must fix the blocking call to accept CancellationToken.
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _cts?.Cancel();
        _workerTask?.GetAwaiter().GetResult(); // sync wait if Dispose is called
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls

### 1. Blocking calls MUST accept `CancellationToken`
```csharp
// ❌ Old: blocks forever, only Thread.Abort could interrupt
var item = queue.Take();

// ✅ New: throws OperationCanceledException when token fires
var item = queue.Take(token);
// — or —
var item = await channel.Reader.ReadAsync(token);
```
If `GetNextItem()` calls something that truly can't be cancelled (e.g., a legacy COM call), you'll be stuck — there is **no .NET 8 equivalent of `Thread.Abort()`**. Wrap it in a sacrificial `Task` as a last resort, but understand the thread leaks.

### 2. `volatile bool` is insufficient
The old `_running` flag has a race: `Stop()` sets it, but the thread is blocked in `GetNextItem()` and never re-checks. `CancellationToken` solves this because it interrupts the blocking call itself.

### 3. `Thread.Sleep` in `Stop()` was a code smell
```csharp
// ❌ Arbitrary sleep, then force-kill
Thread.Sleep(2000);
_workerThread.Abort();

// ✅ Await with timeout — no wasted time, no force-kill
await Task.WhenAny(_workerTask, Task.Delay(timeout));
```

### 4. `ThreadAbortException` auto-rethrew; `OperationCanceledException` does not
In .NET Framework, `ThreadAbortException` re-threw after `catch`/`finally` unless you called `ResetAbort()`. In .NET 8, `OperationCanceledException` is a normal exception — once caught, it's done. Remove any `ResetAbort()` calls.

### 5. If you implement `IHostedService` (recommended for ASP.NET Core)
```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : BackgroundService
{
    protected override async Task ExecuteAsync(CancellationToken stoppingToken)
    {
        while (!stoppingToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            var item = await GetNextItemAsync(stoppingToken);
            await ProcessItemAsync(item, stoppingToken);
        }
    }
}
```
The host manages the lifetime — no manual `Start()`/`Stop()` needed.
